  "text": "where ω is the complex frequency,c is the mean speed of sound, i 2 = −1, and γ is the heat-capacity ratio. p andq are the Fourier-transformed fluctuations 1 of acoustic pressure and heat release rate, respectively. Quantities are non-dimensionalized with a characteristic length, speed of sound, and density. The heat release rate fluctuation is commonly related to a velocity fluctuation at a reference position by a time-delay model [CITATION_1] , i.e. −iω(γ − 1)q = n exp(−iωτ ) ∇p| x ref , where the parameters n and τ are the interaction index and the time delay, respectively. The thermoacoustic stability problem is generally non-Hermitian because of the flame response term and dissipative boundary conditions. On numerical discretization or travelling-wave decomposition [CITATION_2] , thermoacoustic stability is governed by a nonlinear eigenvalue problem [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] L(ω; ε)p = 0,",
